To assess if you should continue against operate the bike business, compare the predicted earnings to the estimated pay of an accountant and the rental revenue from renting the store. The following are the estimated earnings from operating the bike shop: Revenue minus costs equals $200,000 minus $100,000 minus $20,000 equals $80,000 per year. An accountant may expect to earn $40,000 per year. The annual rental revenue from renting the business is $50,000. Based on this data, it looks that running the bike shop would be more lucrative than becoming an accountant or renting out the business. The estimated profit of $80,000 per year from operating the bike shop is more than an accountant's pay or rental income. As a result, it would be more advantageous for you to continue operating the bike shop. 